@adam2392 @amit-sharma Hey guys, the image referred to by Adam is built using the [build-docker-image-docs.yml  workflow](https://github.com/py-why/dowhy/blob/main/.github/workflows/build-docker-image-docs.yml). The Dockerfile it refers to is [docs/Dockerfile](https://github.com/py-why/dowhy/blob/main/docs/Dockerfile).

This Dockerfile builds on top of another Docker image (`ghcr.io/py-why/dowhy-example-notebooks-deps`) where the actual installation of packages happens. You can find its Dockerfile in [py-why/dowhy-example-notebooks-deps-dockerfile](https://github.com/py-why/dowhy-example-notebooks-deps-dockerfile).

If you want to bump the Python version, it should probably happen there. I wouldn't know from the top of my mind how to do it though, as we're never explicitly specifying the Python version. Maybe using a newer Ubuntu base image could do, but unsure. Also have a look at the README, it says that the R dependencies are really difficult to control. Maybe you can delete all these dependencies now, because there is no R code anymore. Otherwise, you'll probably have to go through some trial and error.

Good point, Peter. This is an entry function for beginners, and the idea is that it automatically selects the applicable identification methods and outputs the valid identification strategies. It is useful for users who do not know which method to apply.

But I do see that the implementation is missing :) I think the necessary functionality is already there through AutoIdentifier. @andresmor-ms can you modify this function such that `method` is optional, and if a user does not provide the method then we use the AutoIdentifier with default initialization values (ATE, BACKDOOR_DEFAULT) and output its results? 

